{{primary sources|date=February 2012}} [[File:V. G. Khlopin Radium Institute logo.png|thumb|V. G. Khlopin Radium Institute logo]] The '''V. G. Khlopin Radium Institute''', also known as the '''First Radium Institute''', is a research and production institution located in [[Saint Petersburg]] specializing in the fields of [[nuclear physics]], [[radiochemistry|radio-]] and [[geochemistry]], and on [[ecology|ecological topics]], associated with the problems of nuclear power engineering, [[radioecology]], and [[isotope]] production.<ref>[http://www.istc.ru/istc/db/inst.nsf/wsu/i0001614?OpenDocument&lang=Eng Institution] – ISTC.</ref> It is a subsidiary company of the [[Rosatom]] Russian state corporation.<ref name="about">V. G. Khlopin Radium Institute. [http://www.khlopin.ru/english/index.php About the Institute] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717084109/http://www.khlopin.ru/english/index.php |date=2011-07-17 }}. Retrieved 25 February 2012.</ref>
The Institute was founded as ''State Radium Institute'' in 1922 under the initiative of [[Vladimir Vernadsky|V. I. Vernadskiy]],<ref name="emelyanov">{{cite journal|last=Emelyanov|first=V. S.|title=Nuclear Energy in the Soviet Union|journal=Science and Public Affairs: Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists|date=November 1971|volume=XXVII|number=9|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jQsAAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA38|pages=39|}}</ref> integrating all radiological enterprises present in St. Petersburg (then Petrograd) at that time. This also included a factory in Bondyuga (Tatarstan), which was used by {{Interlanguage link multi|Vitaly Khlopin|2=ru|3=Хлопин, Виталий Григорьевич|preserve=1}} and others to generate Russia's first high-enriched [[radium]] compound.<ref name="foundation">V. G. Khlopin Radium Institute. [http://www.khlopin.ru/english/foundation.php Creation and development of the Institute]. Retrieved 25 February 2012.</ref> The Radium Institute was renamed to V. G. Khlopin in his honor in 1950.<ref name="chronology">V. G. Khlopin Radium Institute. [http://www.khlopin.ru/english/hronology.php Chronology] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110426033000/http://www.khlopin.ru/english/hronology.php |date=2011-04-26 }}. Retrieved 25 February 2012.</ref>
At the Radium Institute, the first European [[cyclotron]] was proposed by [[George Gamow]] and {{Interlanguage link multi|Lev Mysovskii|2=ru|3=Мысовский, Лев Владимирович|preserve=1}} in 1932, being constructed with the help of [[Igor Kurchatov]], operational by 1937.<ref name="chronology" /><ref name="emelyanov"/>
